=Generate a friendly and direct icebreaker for a personalized event invitation email. The message should:
1. Be written in an engaging, professional tone
2. Reference specific details from the person's LinkedIn profile and company
3. End with "Figured I'd reach out."
4. Invite them to speak at our upcoming industry event
5. Within 150 words.
6. Never include this line: I hope this message finds you well! 

Here's information about the recipient:
First name: {{ $('Specific Decision Maker').item.json.profiles[0].name }}
Company description: {{ $('Specific Decision Maker').item.json.profiles[0].employer[0].description }}
Company name: {{ $('Specific Decision Maker').item.json.profiles[0].employer[0].company_name }}
Job Title: {{ $('Specific Decision Maker').item.json.profiles[0].default_position_title }}
Last linkedin post reference for relevancy: {{ $json.posts[0].text }}

Our event is an exclusive conference focused on AI and automation innovations in business processes. We're bringing together thought leaders and practitioners to share cutting-edge approaches and successful implementation strategies.

You have access to a LinkedIn Profile tool. Use this tool to gather additional information about the recipient before writing your message. To use the tool, simply indicate that you want to call the LinkedIn profile tool, then incorporate relevant information from their profile into your message.

Formatting instruction:
Return ONLY a JSON object with a single "icebreaker" key containing the personalized message.

past_employers.employer_linkedin_description: Harvard Model United Nations (HMUN) is the oldest, largest, and most prestigious United Nations simulation for high school students held in the United States., , , , HMUN is a four-day international relations simulation for high school students held annually in downtown Boston. At HMUN, delegates gain insight into the workings of the United Nations and the dynamics of international relations by assuming the roles of UN representatives and members of other international bodies and national cabinets. HMUN is an exciting opportunity for students to debate issues that confront world leaders and to draft resolutions in response to these global issues. Participants will develop their abilities to work with others who are equally motivated and passionate about the topics of debate and to respond to global concerns., , , , HMUN builds upon decades of experience. In 1927, Harvard held its first annual Model League of Nations, followed by the first Model United Nations conference in 1953. This longevity and the dynamic that only a conference of our size can provide make HMUN the preeminent simulation of its kind in the world.

VectorShift is a No-Code Generative AI Platform.

As an Backend Engineer you will build new and work on existing VectorShift’s product lines (e.g., improving workflow run efficiency and scalability, integrate new developments in AI into our platform, manage our database infrastructure).

This will be a challenging and dynamic role, and you will be working at the forefront of distributed systems infrastructure and AI.

Along with building product lines, you can also expect to:

Build integrations of the VectorShift platform with 3rd party applicationsTalk with customers to understanding core pain points and iterating with them on feature requests.Contribute to customer support, especially for the products you build!Stay up to date with the latest developments in AI to integrate new capabilities into our platform.

Responsibilities

Work directly with the founders to conceptualize and implement sub-products and features, end to end.Lead technical architecture decisions, ensuring the platform is scalable and maintainable.Drive forward performance optimization.Establish foundational technical practices that will guide future team members.

Requirements

Degree in a technical discipline, preferably computer science.Experience with Python/ FastAPI.Understanding of performance optimization best practices.Strong communication skills and ability to work in high paced environments.Excellent problem solving skills and proven ability to overcome challenges.

Nice To Have

Experience in early-stage startup environments.Experience with no/low-code platforms.Experience in AI, machine learning, and building RAG workflows.

posts.text:
I was in a 1-1 with a team member and he said he wanted to work from another country for a month.

He started to explain why.

I just said “Approved.”

He tried again to explain why.

I told him “I don’t need to know.”

Many founders think they need everyone in the office 5 days a week.

I completely disagree.

The number one focus for me at VectorShift is: are we helping companies automate their workflows with AI.

You decide how you work:

A different country every month?
Approved.

From your childhood bedroom?
Approved.

3 hours off to take your dog to the vet?
Approved.

The only thing that matters is output.

Founders should only care if their employees improve the customer experience.

Last week, an 18 year old who built a $30M ARR business got REJECTED from Harvard and every other elite college he applied to.

I sure didn’t meet anyone who came close to his level of agency and drive when I was at Harvard.

In fact, I would like to see the average Harvard student, who desperately tries to be a worker bee at Big Tech, MBB, or a large bank accomplish anything remotely close.

Admissions officers at these “elite” colleges have totally lost the plot.

Instead, they’d rather admit candidates who:
- Promised to “cure cancer” in their essay but was first in line at the Goldman Sachs networking session
- Explored the “intersection” between math and literature when in reality, they aren’t good at either
- Diligently followed the rules: did well in school/SAT, won traditional awards, and hired a 5-figure college consultant to wrap their boring package into a good “story”

After starting VectorShift, I realized: starting up is the great equalizer.

Customers don’t care about your “interdisciplinary passions.”
Customers don’t care that you won the quiz bowl.
Customers don’t care about your sob story about “personal identity.”

Customers only care that your product solves their problems.

Everyone starts from the same place. Nothing you did before matters. Anyone can start up.

“Failed” previously? Didn’t get your dream job? Didn’t go to an Ivy league college? That’s ok. The only thing that matters is if you have what it takes now.

Recently, an 18 year old built a $30M ARR business and got REJECTED from Harvard and every elite college he applied to.

Many people find this shocking.

As a former Harvard student, I don’t. Why?

Top colleges often select candidates for deterministic reasons:
Who your parents are.
Where you were born.
What background you come from.

At Harvard, I often came across:
- 8th generation legacy students whose great great great great great grandfather also went to Harvard
- Kids of public company CEOs & global political leaders
- Kid who grew up on a farm in rural Idaho so the admissions department could put his photo on brochures to show that Harvard is “geographically diverse”

Harvard admissions officers enforce quotas for “underrepresented” geographies, countries, and races.

In my high school, Asians had to achieve higher GPAs / SAT scores vs non-Asians to get admitted.

The result?

True competence is crowded out.  

Admissions should be simple: what did you do? Not: where did you come from?

A YC company was quoted $63k for a custom AI invoice automation

Their intern built it in 5 minutes

With VectorShift, employees forward invoices to a designated email and GPT4o:
- Extracts vendor name + amount from the invoices
- Matches the invoice against POs in Quickbooks
- Approves or rejects the invoice + adds data to a Google Sheet

“Stop hiring humans. Use AI.” Shopify’s CEO, Tobi Lutke, told employees in a leaked memo.

If you think he’s wrong, I’m sorry to tell you your role will be obsolete.

In the memo, Lutke wrote:
1. Before hiring a human, justify why AI can’t perform the same tasks
2. Every human must use AI
3. Every human will be assessed on how much they use AI

Between 2022-2024, Shopify laid off 3,500 employees (30% of its workforce).

If you aren’t using AI today, you’ll be the first to be fired in the future.

People most at risk of losing their jobs to AI in corporate:
- Middle-managers who spend their days “managing up” and churning out PowerPoints for execs who don’t read them
- That guy in meetings who just rephrases what everyone else says and then sends a meeting recap email to go “above and beyond”
- Strategy analysts who churn out 50-page reports predicting market trends that AI can nail in 30 seconds with better accuracy
- The "culture cheerleader" who orchestrates forced happy hours

Tired of corporate politics? Doing real work?

I have good news for you. You will be valued 10x more.
